{% block content %}
  <h2>Who we are</h2>
  <p>The rest of this hub is open to anyone: the treaty orientation, the community pages, the land section. The Circle is the room where members act. In 2023 the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations reached a ten billion dollar settlement for unpaid annuities, shared across all 21 signatory communities. The money has flowed to the communities. Many members across the treaty have said the same thing: we do not yet have a clear picture of how the funds are governed, what the rules are, or what we are entitled to see. The Circle exists to turn that shared concern into clear, respectful, member-led questions.</p>

  <div class="card card--magenta">
    <h3>What we are, and are not</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>We are members and beneficiaries, organizing across communities as one voice.</li>
      <li>We are not a band council committee, the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund, or any community's administration. Those are the bodies we ask questions of.</li>
      <li>This is about transparency and member information, not about removing or attacking any leader.</li>
      <li>We work from sourced facts and we ask questions. We do not make accusations, and we name no private individuals.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Principles</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Member-led and beneficiary-focused.</li>
    <li>Sourced facts, framed as questions. No accusations, and no naming of private individuals.</li>
    <li>Respectful of each community's own governance and of the right of members to information.</li>
    <li>Independent of councils, the Litigation Fund, and any tribal organization.</li>
    <li>Open to any member of a Robinson Huron Treaty First Nation who shares these principles.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to take part</h2>
  <p>Any beneficiary who shares these principles can take part. The idea is simple: bring one or two members from your community who are willing to be a local contact, and use the shared standard so every community is asking the same plain questions in the same respectful way, so no one is asking alone.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Read <a href="/standard">the shared standard</a> and the one-page invitation.</li>
    <li>Find one or two members in your community willing to be a local contact.</li>
    <li>Make contact with the Circle so your community is represented on the joint letter to the Litigation Fund.</li>
    <li>Put Part 2 of the standard to your own Chief and Council, and share what comes back.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Become a local contact</h2>
  <p>A local contact is simply a member who is willing to be the point of contact for the Circle in their community: to share the shared standard, gather members who want to take part, and pass along what their council responds. You do not need to speak for anyone or take a position on any leader. The role is to help members in your community ask the same plain questions, together.</p>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/get-involved">How to join</a>
    <a class="btn btn--alt" href="/standard">Read the shared standard</a>
  </div>

  <p class="muted">The Circle began with members of Sagamok Anishnawbek and is opening to every Robinson Huron Treaty First Nation. This page is a starting draft to share and revise together.</p>
